WEBVTT

00:32.290 --> 00:32.771
Christmas.

00:35.314 --> 00:37.416
Here's something that you might not know about Christmas.

00:38.898 --> 00:45.647
For the first few hundred years of the church, Christians largely did not celebrate it.

00:47.269 --> 00:47.910
Merry Christmas.

00:50.513 --> 00:56.320
No nativity scenes, no special services, not even a feast.

00:57.942 --> 01:01.106
Early Christians didn't celebrate anyone's birthday, actually.

01:02.082 --> 01:03.003
Not even Jesus.

01:04.285 --> 01:10.552
They celebrated the day someone died, which is a weird thing to say to celebrate the day someone died.

01:11.152 --> 01:15.357
But the reason is, is for Christians, the day someone died, it was their heavenly birthday.

01:17.419 --> 01:22.645
So the earliest Christians absolutely celebrated something, but it wasn't in Bethlehem.

01:23.727 --> 01:24.528
It was the cross.

01:25.829 --> 01:26.850
It was the resurrection.

01:28.572 --> 01:30.194
Christmas the holiday.

01:30.370 --> 01:34.035
that the whole world knows today actually came much later.

01:35.217 --> 01:47.095
Before the fourth century, Christians in the east celebrated something called Epiphany, which basically rolled together Jesus' birth, his baptism, and the visit of the Magi.

01:47.135 --> 01:51.641
But in Rome, in the west, no Christmas.

01:52.743 --> 01:53.885
And then something happened.

01:55.067 --> 02:00.114
The church found itself in a heated debate about one essential question.

02:01.154 --> 02:03.497
Who exactly is Jesus?

02:04.919 --> 02:05.660
Fully God?

02:06.461 --> 02:07.141
Fully man?

02:07.842 --> 02:08.864
Somewhere in between?

02:08.924 --> 02:16.873
The debates were raging, and in the moment Christians rediscovered the truth at the center of their faith.

02:17.995 --> 02:20.938
God became flesh.

02:22.881 --> 02:26.545
The eternal Son stepped into time and space.

02:28.007 --> 02:30.290
So for the first time believers in Rome,

02:30.402 --> 02:33.366
Set aside a day to celebrate Jesus' birth.

02:33.967 --> 02:35.730
And they chose December 25th.

02:37.112 --> 02:39.295
Not because they knew his exact birthday.

02:39.335 --> 02:43.882
You can see all sorts of people if you want to debate when Jesus was actually born.

02:44.483 --> 02:45.765
Some will say like March.

02:46.105 --> 02:50.712
I even read somewhere September recently, which I really want to dig into and find that out more.

02:51.774 --> 02:57.202
But it doesn't matter because it wasn't to get his birth date precise.

02:57.698 --> 03:03.065
Instead, the Roman world already celebrated the winter solstice.

03:03.085 --> 03:18.143
It was the unconquered sun where light begins pushing back the darkness, and Christians looked at that season that time, and they said, that's the perfect day to celebrate the true light of the world.

03:20.526 --> 03:22.168
So they didn't cancel the festival.

03:23.409 --> 03:24.270
They transformed it.

03:25.632 --> 03:27.314
And by the end of the fourth century,

03:27.458 --> 03:43.304
Christmas spread across the Christian world, not as a sentimental tradition, but as a bold declaration that God came, that God entered, that God drew near, that God took on flesh.

03:45.107 --> 03:46.369
But here's what's fascinating.

03:47.371 --> 03:54.002
From the very beginning, the church celebrated Christmas because of what came after Christmas.

03:55.042 --> 03:58.767
The manger mattered because the tomb is empty.

04:00.310 --> 04:03.154
The birth mattered because of the resurrection.

04:03.234 --> 04:06.999
Christmas was never meant to stand alone.

04:07.540 --> 04:13.669
It was always meant to be the beginning of God's story of our salvation.

04:15.331 --> 04:22.802
And that means the manger isn't just a doctrine that we believe, or we go around saying, Jesus is the reason for the season,

04:24.130 --> 04:28.997
It's a doorway to the God who steps into real human life.

04:30.799 --> 04:36.107
So in Luke chapter two, the angels announce the arrival of the Savior.

04:36.727 --> 04:43.397
And then in 1 Corinthians 15, our core passage today, Paul tells us what that Savior accomplished.

04:44.699 --> 04:48.344
The message of Christmas isn't simply that Jesus was born.

04:48.384 --> 04:53.010
It's that the one who was born is the one who conquered death.

04:53.538 --> 05:04.010
And that truth isn't just something the early church believed, it's something we still have to learn how to live with, especially when life is heavy.

05:06.012 --> 05:14.761
Now that's all fascinating history about when Christmas as a December 25th holiday came to fruition, but here's why it really matters.

05:15.802 --> 05:19.026
I love Christmas, I really do, honestly.

05:19.266 --> 05:23.653
But I've had years where the joy of the season collided with the real weight of life.

05:24.794 --> 05:30.964
And knowing you all, I know that that's true of you too, whether right now or whether in previous years.

05:32.426 --> 05:41.059
And because Christmas didn't start as a feel-good holiday, it didn't start as a season of nostalgia, lights, or warm traditions.

05:42.000 --> 05:44.504
It started as a declaration of hope.

05:45.426 --> 05:48.370
A hope big enough to hold the weight of real life.

05:49.218 --> 05:54.303
And if we're being honest for many of us, that's exactly what we need right now is that hope.

05:55.905 --> 06:07.016
The hope, not a frail hope, but a hope that what God has already done gives us hope for what will come.

06:10.179 --> 06:17.266
Because while Christmas is supposed to be a season of joy, it's also the season where life feels heaviest.

06:18.050 --> 06:23.397
For some of us in this room, Christmas is a reminder of someone who isn't here anymore.

06:25.679 --> 06:35.812
Our relationship that didn't heal, or a dream that didn't work out, or a struggle that won't go away.

06:37.374 --> 06:47.186
For some of us, Christmas exposes financial pressure, family, tension, loneliness, questions about the future,

06:47.842 --> 06:49.403
that we don't know the answer to.

06:51.205 --> 06:52.947
And I've had Christmases like that too.

06:53.707 --> 06:55.569
In fact, honestly, this one's felt like it.

06:56.130 --> 06:59.012
We have had illness run through our house since mid-November.

07:00.013 --> 07:04.337
It has been like one of us getting sick after the other after the other after the other.

07:04.357 --> 07:06.560
I think we're playing illness volleyball.

07:07.160 --> 07:10.463
It's not a fun game, but we decided to play it this season.

07:15.208 --> 07:17.810
And in those seasons, the questions of our hearts

07:18.754 --> 07:20.857
get louder than the songs on the radio.

07:22.499 --> 07:33.174
And the thing is, you can feel all of that, all of that heaviness, all that weightiness, all of those questions, all that turmoil while you're sitting next to a twinkling Christmas tree.

07:36.419 --> 07:42.788
I've had Christmases like that where everything around me felt festive, but inside, life was anything but simple.

07:44.450 --> 07:47.154
Because the lights are beautiful, the music is familiar,

07:47.426 --> 07:53.593
The traditions are comforting, but none of that fixes the questions we carry into the season.

07:54.274 --> 07:55.556
Will things ever get better?

07:56.216 --> 07:59.080
Is there any real hope for my situation?

07:59.761 --> 08:00.982
Has God forgotten me?

08:02.144 --> 08:05.187
Does any of this faith stuff actually change anything?

08:06.128 --> 08:07.510
Or is it just something we say?

08:07.570 --> 08:14.258
And this is where the Christmas story, the real Christmas story, speaks louder than sentiment.

08:14.626 --> 08:19.412
But as God did not send angels to say, unto you is born a new holiday.

08:19.472 --> 08:28.622
He didn't send shepherds home singing carols and sipping cocoa, although who doesn't like hot cocoa?

08:28.682 --> 08:29.143
I mean, come on.

08:30.685 --> 08:32.366
No, he sent them a savior.

08:32.386 --> 08:37.172
A savior born into a world as broken as ours is today.

08:37.192 --> 08:42.418
A savior who came not to decorate our lives, but to deliver us.

08:43.746 --> 08:50.755
a Savior whose birth was never meant to stand alone because the manger was always pointing towards something more.

08:52.757 --> 08:54.759
And this is the tension that we live in today.

08:55.440 --> 09:01.688
It's possible to celebrate the birth of Jesus and still miss out on the hope of Jesus.

09:03.570 --> 09:08.937
It's possible to love the Christmas story and still struggle to believe it changes our story.

09:10.519 --> 09:13.202
Let's be honest, that's where some of us are

09:13.474 --> 09:14.836
right now, today.

09:16.359 --> 09:19.003
So the question we wrestle with today is simple and honest.

09:19.424 --> 09:21.687
What kind of hope does Christmas really offer us?

09:23.029 --> 09:32.425
A seasonal uplift, a sentimental escape from reality, or something strong enough to anchor us in the hardest places of life.

09:33.967 --> 09:40.818
Luke 2 gives us the announcement, and we're going to read it in a moment, but 1 Corinthians 15 shows us the outcome.

09:41.762 --> 09:48.513
Christmas shows us that God came near and Easter shows us why he came.

09:50.196 --> 09:56.687
And when you put these two together, you get the kind of hope that actually carries ordinary people like us through real life.

09:58.129 --> 09:59.852
That's the hope we're going to talk about today.

10:00.713 --> 10:08.306
So I want us to take a moment this morning and slow down and listen again to the story where the hope was first announced.

10:08.674 --> 10:15.584
to do your best to imagine Linus has come out with his blanket ready to tell you the story this morning.

10:17.847 --> 10:22.674
Here's what it says in Luke chapter two verses eight through 20.

10:24.076 --> 10:30.865
In the same region shepherds were staying out in the fields and keeping watch at night over their flock.

10:31.947 --> 10:37.074
Then an angel of the Lord stood before them and the glory of the Lord shone around them

10:37.794 --> 10:42.940
And they were terrified, but the angel said to them, do not be afraid.

10:43.701 --> 10:47.986
I proclaim to you good news of great joy that will be for all people.

10:48.726 --> 10:54.813
Today in the city of David, a Savior was born for you who is the Messiah, the Lord.

10:54.874 --> 10:57.917
This will be a sign for you.

10:58.277 --> 11:02.322
You will find a baby wrapped tightly in cloth and lying in a manger.

11:03.074 --> 11:14.449
Suddenly there was a multitude of the heavenly hosts with the angel praising God and saying, Glory to God in the highest heaven and peace on earth to people he favors.

11:15.671 --> 11:25.885
When the angels had left them and returned to heaven, the shepherd said to one another, let's go straight to Bethlehem and see what has happened, which the Lord has made known to us.

11:26.826 --> 11:32.914
They hurried off and found both Mary and Joseph and the baby who was lying in the manger.

11:33.538 --> 11:41.630
After seeing them, they reported the message they were told about this child, and all who heard it were amazed at what the shepherds said to them.

11:42.391 --> 11:47.618
But Mary was treasuring up all these things in her heart and meditating on them.

11:48.460 --> 11:57.913
The shepherds returned, glorifying and praising God for all the things they had seen and heard, which were just as they had been told.

11:59.796 --> 12:01.138
So right there, Luke

12:01.890 --> 12:05.296
shows us how hope arrived, and we'll come back to it in a moment.

12:05.877 --> 12:11.386
But I want to turn for a moment and read how Paul shows us what hope accomplished.

12:12.829 --> 12:25.490
He writes in 1 Corinthians 15, 3 through 4, for I pass on to you as most important what I also receive, that Christ died for our sins according to the Scriptures.

12:25.986 --> 12:30.450
that he was buried, that he was raised on the third day according to the scriptures.

12:30.891 --> 12:36.236
And moving ahead to verse 20, he says, but as it is, Christ has been raised from the dead.

12:36.276 --> 12:40.320
The first fruits of those who have fallen asleep.

12:41.361 --> 12:46.826
For since death came through a man, the resurrection of the dead also came through a man.

12:47.126 --> 12:54.994
For just as in Adam all die, so also in Christ all will be made alive.

12:56.898 --> 13:06.273
Before we talk about what Christmas means for us today, we need to see what the Scripture is actually telling us, because Luke 2 in 1 Corinthians 15 are not disconnected stories.

13:07.295 --> 13:09.638
There are two chapters of the same rescue mission.

13:10.179 --> 13:23.080
In fact, what's really intriguing about Luke is Luke, the writer of the Gospel of Luke, is also the writer of the Book of Acts, which chronicles Paul's story, the Paul who wrote 1 Corinthians 15.

13:23.120 --> 13:24.402
In fact, Luke

13:24.994 --> 13:33.546
begins using the first person plural we when he's telling the story of Paul's journey as if he is with him on the journey.

13:35.309 --> 13:44.381
So it's kind of cool to hear what Luke writes about the birth of Jesus and to see what Paul Luke's companion has to say about the resurrection.

13:45.783 --> 13:53.394
One begins in a manger and the other ends at an empty tomb and both reveal the same savior.

13:53.762 --> 13:55.044
So let's start with Luke 2.

13:56.205 --> 14:01.311
In Luke 2, in the first couple verses, we get the announcement of hope.

14:02.412 --> 14:06.297
When the angels appear the shepherds, they say, do not be afraid.

14:06.317 --> 14:10.282
I bring you good news that will bring joy to all people.

14:11.523 --> 14:16.449
The Savior, the Messiah, the Lord, has been born today in Bethlehem.

14:17.911 --> 14:23.698
Right away, Luke shows us something stunning in the angel's declaration to the shepherds.

14:24.098 --> 14:42.325
God announces the birth of Jesus, not to the powerful, not to the religious elite, not to the people that anybody reading this book in the ancient world would expect, but to shepherds, to lowly shepherds, to the poor, the overlooked, the unseen.

14:42.365 --> 14:51.538
This is God's way of saying the Savior is for everyone, especially those who think He couldn't possibly be for them.

14:53.538 --> 14:55.621
And spiritually speaking, that's all of us.

14:56.562 --> 15:00.687
The shepherds respond by doing the very first thing disciples always do.

15:01.288 --> 15:09.279
They go to see Jesus, they receive the good news by what they witness, and then they run and they tell everyone what they have seen.

15:11.862 --> 15:17.710
Luke says that they spread the word and could not stop talking about what was revealed to them.

15:18.030 --> 15:18.290
Why?

15:18.310 --> 15:21.074
Because what they saw wasn't just a baby.

15:22.402 --> 15:24.825
It was the beginning of God's promise rescue.

15:26.427 --> 15:29.711
They had heard the angels proclaim two realities at once.

15:30.792 --> 15:38.202
Glory to God in the highest, what is happening in heaven, and peace on earth, what God is doing here through Jesus.

15:38.742 --> 15:40.945
Christmas is not a sentiment.

15:41.205 --> 15:42.407
It is not nostalgia.

15:42.667 --> 15:44.269
It is not a comforting tradition.

15:44.610 --> 15:51.378
It is God stepping into human history to fulfill every promise he ever made.

15:54.658 --> 15:58.064
But announcement only matters if it leads to action.

15:59.006 --> 16:01.611
And that's where Paul takes us in 1 Corinthians 15.

16:02.893 --> 16:07.041
Paul says, Christ died for our sins according to the scriptures.

16:08.103 --> 16:08.784
He was buried.

16:09.305 --> 16:12.270
He was raised on the third day according to the scriptures.

16:12.671 --> 16:18.802
Paul is telling the Corinthians and us that the Christmas story was always meant to lead somewhere.

16:19.682 --> 16:23.767
The birth in Bethlehem leads to the cross in Jerusalem.

16:23.807 --> 16:25.909
And the cross leads to the tomb.

16:25.969 --> 16:29.092
And the tomb leads to resurrection life.

16:29.773 --> 16:34.198
Paul is drawing a straight line from the manger to the empty tomb.

16:37.001 --> 16:38.323
In fact, here's a fun fact.

16:39.944 --> 16:41.766
I love being nerdy, sorry.

16:42.968 --> 16:45.010
The funny thing about the tomb

16:45.730 --> 16:55.900
is that oftentimes when we read about the inn where Jesus was born, we get our minds set on like a hotel and there's no room there.

16:56.420 --> 17:05.769
What actually happened was that Jesus was born in a cave or a tomb-like structure, rock hewn out where animals were at.

17:07.591 --> 17:15.218
He was almost born in a tomb and then, well, raised from the dead to leave.

17:15.298 --> 17:15.739
a tomb.

17:16.500 --> 17:17.541
Kind of a fun little fact.

17:17.641 --> 17:19.263
Anyway, Merry Christmas again.

17:20.044 --> 17:26.253
So, the child who was born is the Christ who died.

17:26.313 --> 17:30.118
The Christ who died is the Lord who rose.

17:31.199 --> 17:33.903
And the Lord who rose is the King who now reigns.

17:35.345 --> 17:38.909
This story is not a myth, it's not just mere symbolism.

17:39.470 --> 17:42.354
Paul roots it in eyewitness testimony.

17:44.066 --> 17:54.796
He heard from the first of Jesus' disciples on through the other people and then was the last to witness the resurrected Jesus.

17:55.977 --> 17:58.420
He says he's the last and the loneliest of all.

18:00.802 --> 18:05.547
Hundreds of people, many still alive at the time that Paul's writing, saw Jesus risen.

18:07.008 --> 18:09.771
Christianity does not rest on warm holiday feelings.

18:10.131 --> 18:13.234
It stands or falls on the historical resurrection of Christ.

18:13.890 --> 18:24.045
which leads Paul to his next point, which is when he writes that Christ has indeed been raised from the dead, the first fruits of those who have fallen asleep.

18:24.706 --> 18:28.492
For as in Adam all dies, so in Christ all will be made alive.

18:28.952 --> 18:36.684
In other words, Jesus's resurrection is not just his victory, it is the guarantee of ours.

18:39.228 --> 18:40.850
He is the first fruits.

18:41.602 --> 18:44.446
The opening chapter of a harvest that's coming.

18:45.347 --> 18:50.133
The resurrection is not only a past event, it is a future promise.

18:52.376 --> 18:55.760
And that future promise flows directly from the birth that happened in Luke 2.

18:56.561 --> 19:06.354
The baby born in Bethlehem is the beginning of new creation, a world where death is defeated and where every person who belongs to Christ will rise with him one day.

19:08.450 --> 19:13.535
So when you put Luke 2 and 1 Corinthians 15 together, the message is unmistakable.

19:15.096 --> 19:20.161
We have hope announced at Christmas that is fulfilled in Easter.

19:20.521 --> 19:24.045
The Savior born in a manger is the Savior raised from the dead.

19:24.105 --> 19:28.049
The child wrapped in cloths is the king who conquered death.

19:28.849 --> 19:31.171
Christmas is not complete without resurrection.

19:32.172 --> 19:35.235
And resurrection doesn't make sense without incarnation.

19:36.557 --> 19:38.098
That God came in the flesh.

19:38.306 --> 19:41.210
and together they reveal the whole of the gospel.

19:42.913 --> 19:54.489
God comes near, God dies for us, God rises for us, God reigns for us, and God will one day raise us to.

19:55.311 --> 19:59.236
This is not a seasonal story, it is a salvation story.

19:59.977 --> 20:03.122
It is the story of a God who keeps his promises

20:03.202 --> 20:09.348
from the manger to the cross to the empty tomb to your and my life today.

20:12.531 --> 20:17.196
So when he traced the story from Bethlehem to the empty tomb, one truth becomes impossible to miss.

20:17.536 --> 20:18.657
It's our bottom line today.

20:19.117 --> 20:23.101
Hope began in a manger and became realized at the empty tomb.

20:24.443 --> 20:28.907
Hope began in the manger and became realized at the empty tomb.

20:29.447 --> 20:32.210
So if Christmas is the beginning of hope,

20:32.386 --> 20:34.689
And the resurrection is the fulfillment of that hope.

20:34.990 --> 20:37.113
What does that actually mean for us this week?

20:39.597 --> 20:42.180
It means the gospel doesn't just explain our faith.

20:42.621 --> 20:46.607
It reshapes how we live inside our real circumstances.

20:47.528 --> 20:54.859
It means more than a beautiful story, more than a cherished tradition, more than a theological truth we affirm.

20:55.420 --> 20:57.122
It means hope is not seasonal.

20:57.944 --> 20:58.885
It's available now.

21:01.569 --> 21:02.290
It's alive.

21:03.426 --> 21:08.992
It's present, it's personal, and it is stronger than whatever you walked in carrying today.

21:11.715 --> 21:13.057
Here's what it looks like in real life.

21:14.258 --> 21:16.580
Because of the manger, you are not alone.

21:16.640 --> 21:18.823
You are not alone.

21:19.684 --> 21:21.866
Christmas means that God came near.

21:22.607 --> 21:30.135
That's why we celebrate that theological word incarnation because God came in the flesh and he came near.

21:31.457 --> 21:32.658
Even the lowliest

21:33.666 --> 21:40.374
of people matter to God, even if they feel overlooked in the world they reside.

21:40.774 --> 21:48.744
He came near to the poor, near to the overlooked, near to the anxious, near to the exhausted, near to the broken.

21:48.764 --> 21:57.554
So when you feel forgotten or unseen or buried under the pressure,

21:57.762 --> 22:04.248
The incarnation tells you God stepped into your world so you would never walk through it alone.

22:04.308 --> 22:06.550
Never ever.

22:08.292 --> 22:10.614
That's not poetic, it's absolutely practical.

22:10.955 --> 22:21.745
It means that in every fear, every decision, every hardship that you face, here, tomorrow, yesterday, and beyond, God is with you.

22:24.087 --> 22:26.770
It also means that because of the cross, you are deeply loved.

22:28.162 --> 22:30.925
Jesus wasn't just born, he came to give his life.

22:31.746 --> 22:33.448
The manger points to the mission.

22:34.088 --> 22:37.632
The child of Bethlehem grew up to carry the cross in Jerusalem.

22:38.233 --> 22:42.637
And the cross tells you, your sin does not disqualify you from God's love.

22:43.098 --> 22:45.100
It is the very reason that Christ came.

22:46.441 --> 22:54.930
So when you feel unworthy or ashamed or spiritually stuck, Christmas leads you

22:55.106 --> 22:59.811
to the cross where Jesus says, I came because you couldn't fix yourself.

23:00.672 --> 23:02.574
And I love you enough to make you new.

23:05.217 --> 23:10.942
And that hope also tells us that because of the empty tomb, your future is secure.

23:12.544 --> 23:22.034
This is where 1 Corinthians 15 speaks directly into our daily fears, our fear of death, our fear of disease, our fear of loss,

23:22.338 --> 23:25.664
are fear of what comes next, a fear of the unknown.

23:26.124 --> 23:28.488
The resurrection answers all of it.

23:29.450 --> 23:46.098
Paul calls Jesus the first fruits, meaning that his resurrection is not just life altering and world altering, it is a preview, the guarantee, the down payment of your resurrected life.

23:48.802 --> 23:54.428
If Christ is alive and hope is alive and if Christ rose, then you will rise too.

23:55.629 --> 24:00.815
And if Christ conquered death, then death does not have the last word over your story.

24:02.697 --> 24:04.319
That is not abstract doctrine.

24:05.220 --> 24:07.582
It is everyday courage.

24:07.602 --> 24:12.788
It means you can face tomorrow without fear of ultimate loss because God's got this.

24:15.271 --> 24:18.514
Because of that same hope, because Christ is risen,

24:18.882 --> 24:20.884
Your suffering is not pointless.

24:21.184 --> 24:24.327
Christmas tells us God entered into suffering.

24:24.928 --> 24:28.391
The resurrection tells us God will end suffering.

24:29.432 --> 24:34.277
So when life hurts, and for many people, the holidays magnify the hurt.

24:34.437 --> 24:41.644
Because everybody's telling you that you should feel happy, that you should buy stuff, that everything should be roses all the time.

24:42.865 --> 24:45.808
But the gospel reminds you that your pain is not wasted.

24:45.868 --> 24:48.210
Your tears are not unnoticed.

24:48.482 --> 24:52.868
Your story is not over, and resurrection is coming.

24:55.651 --> 24:58.034
This gives real comfort and real grief.

24:58.935 --> 25:06.385
And lastly, because of Jesus, you have a hope that walks with you, not just a hope, you remember.

25:07.546 --> 25:12.613
Christmas is not a sentimental escape, and Easter is not a theological footnote.

25:13.013 --> 25:16.818
Together they give you living hope that studies your emotions

25:16.994 --> 25:24.923
anchors your identity in Christ, reframes your circumstances, strengthens your faith, and restores your joy.

25:24.983 --> 25:32.371
It carries you through any hardship that you're facing, and it reminds you who holds the future in his hands.

25:35.294 --> 25:41.581
This is the hope that began in a manger and was secured forever at an empty tomb.

25:43.243 --> 25:46.226
So here's a simple question for us this Christmas.

25:47.426 --> 25:51.712
Where do you need the hope of Christmas to meet you right now?

25:53.755 --> 25:54.897
Are you worried about your future?

25:56.879 --> 26:03.569
Does a relationship that you have feel fragile is grief heavier for you during the holidays?

26:04.650 --> 26:05.592
I know it is for many.

26:08.095 --> 26:10.458
Is there a sin that you cannot seem to shake?

26:13.443 --> 26:15.826
Alonliness that you're trying to hide

26:17.538 --> 26:19.781
A situation that you can't quite fix.

26:21.844 --> 26:23.606
Is there a fear that you can't shake?

26:25.790 --> 26:29.194
Christmas isn't asking you to pretend everything is fine.

26:30.897 --> 26:33.160
Even if that's the messaging of the world around us.

26:34.321 --> 26:38.667
If you're carrying any of that today, you're not failing at faith.

26:39.028 --> 26:42.052
You're exactly where the story meets you.

26:44.055 --> 26:46.258
Christmas is telling you that hope came for you.

26:46.850 --> 26:50.315
And the resurrection tells you hope is alive for you.

26:51.737 --> 27:00.569
The God who came near in Bethlehem is the God who defeated death in Jerusalem and the God who walks with you today.

27:01.411 --> 27:05.156
When he came in, I hope that you got a communion packet.

27:09.161 --> 27:15.250
When we take communion each Sunday, we are obedient to the command of Jesus

27:15.682 --> 27:19.828
to eat the bread and drink of the cup in remembrance of Him.

27:19.868 --> 27:26.899
But when we take communion, we proclaim the gospel message from the manger to the empty tomb.

27:26.939 --> 27:35.693
Because we recognize that Jesus came in the flesh to give His life as a ransom for many.

27:35.713 --> 27:44.146
And we proclaim that God the Father took up His life by the power of the Spirit on the third day and the tomb was empty.

27:45.890 --> 27:55.788
When we take communion, we remember the Christmas story and the gospel message and the hope we have in the resurrection.

27:57.171 --> 28:05.005
So I'm gonna give you a moment to pause and reflect on the goodness of God and the wonderful message at Christmas.

28:06.027 --> 28:09.874
And after that moment of reflection, we'll take communion together as one church family.

29:08.770 --> 29:13.194
I invite each and every one of you to take the bread and eat.

29:13.214 --> 29:16.297
This represents his body, which is given for us.

29:24.725 --> 29:27.888
And in like manner, I invite you to take and drink from this cup.

29:28.449 --> 29:30.791
This represents his blood, which is poured out for us.

29:37.057 --> 29:37.938
Please pray with me.

29:39.522 --> 29:46.229
your Lord God, we thank you for this morning where we can worship you through song.

29:47.651 --> 29:55.339
Hear your word and reflect on this Christmas story that we celebrate each time, each year at this time.

29:55.399 --> 30:05.970
And Lord, I pray that as we go about doing the things that we do and living out the hustle of this season,

30:07.330 --> 30:35.122
I pray that you'll give us moments to pause and to reflect, not just on the story, but on the truth that you have come near to us, that even though life gets hectic, that it gets difficult, that we have seemingly unanswerable questions about life, relationships, health, whatever it is,

30:36.290 --> 30:42.399
that you haven't left us to our own devices, but that you broke into our world with grace.

30:44.582 --> 31:05.874
And I pray that that story, that truth, that moment in time that is still living today, I pray that it will lift us up, give us hope, and help us to walk through life, not only to glorify you, but

31:06.050 --> 31:07.153
within your strength.

31:08.557 --> 31:13.311
We thank you so much for loving us, and we thank you so much for sending your son Jesus.

31:14.134 --> 31:15.398
And it's in his name that we pray.

31:16.541 --> 31:16.882
Amen.

